  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">STAR Call 1- Promoting Decent Language and Issues-based Campaigning for Peaceful Elections in</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Despite having held six successive Presidential and Parliamentary elections, which have been touted as largely peaceful, Ghana is still faced with major challenges during elections. Factors such as the escalation of hate speech and abusive campaign language, resort to unsubstantiated allegations by the media and political party actors, and general unprofessional media conduct during electioneering campaigns, remain a threat of violence during elections in Ghana. Particularly, the 2012 elections witnessed an escalation of hate speech, ethnocentric comments, insults, violence-prone political propaganda perpetrated mainly through radio. At the same time, there was an increase in unprofessional media conduct. These developments among others increased the potential for violence during the 2012 elections. The MFWA thus embarked on a campaign language monitoring intervention that was widely praised as having contributed significantly to mitigating potential violence in the 2012 electioneering process. The project involved monitoring hate speech and other violence-prone campaign language on 31 influential radio stations across the country. Political parties and their communicators who used such language on radio were named a</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The expected changes/outcomes of this proposed project are: a) Incidents of campaign related hate speech and other indecent campaign messages reduced by at least 70% reduction (from baseline figure); b) At least 90% of the radio stations being monitored openly disallow the use of hate speech and other inciting campaign messages on their networks; c) There is reduced incidents of hate speech and other inciting electoral campaign messages in Ghana contributing a peaceful election in 2016</narrative>
  </description>
